<DOC><DOCNO> AP900712-0085 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-90 1325EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-Train-Van 1stLd-Writethru a0555 07-12 0289</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Train-Van, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0555,0293</SECOND><HEAD>Train Hits Van Loaded With Children, Three Killed</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf, `Three adults...', with outing to an amusementpark sted at; INSERTS one graf after 6th, `A witness...', to UPDATEwith driver surviving, victims related. Picks up 7th graf, `Eightpassengers...'.</NOTE><DATELINE>SHREVEPORT, La. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A van loaded with children was crushedwhen it drove into the path of a train, authorities said. Twochildren and a 25-year-old woman were killed.   Three adults and five children remained hospitalized today inserious or critical condition. They were on a family outing to anamusement park.   The engineer of the 65-car Southern Pacific train tried to warnthe driver as she approached the crossing Wednesday evening, saidrailroad company spokesman Jim Johnson.   ``According to the engineer, he was blowing his horn and ringinghis bell when he saw the van approach...,'' Johnson said. ``Shenever stopped.''   The engineer threw on his emergency brakes, but the train hitthe van broadside, crushing it and flipping it, Johnson and rescueworkers said.   ``A witness reported the van was eastbound on Stagecoach Roadand drove into the path of the northbound freight train,'' saidSgt. Mike Middleton.   Caddo Parish sheriff's deputies said the driver survived butthey have not been able to interview her because of her injuries.Investigators said the victims were related.   Eight passengers were thrown from the van, and three were pinnedin the wreckage, said Thurman Speaks, chief of Fire District 6.   Killed were Sandra Stultz and her 18-month-old daughter, Hannah,of Texarkana, Ark., and 8-year-old Amy Gray of Taylor, Ark.   The railroad crossing south of this northwest Louisiana city wasequipped with a crossing warning sign and a stop sign.</TEXT></DOC>